Latent Class Model

Fit the data two ways: 1) Likelihood based method and 2) MCMC using JAGS.

Likelihood based method (randomLCA package)

(mod.lcm <- randomLCA(X, nclass = 2, probit = TRUE, seed = 123))

It seems that Class 1 (\(\delta = 1\)) is the diseased class and Class 2 (\(\delta = 2\)) is non-diseased. The estimate of the prevalence \(\tau := P(\delta = 1)\) is 0.479. Thus, the sensitivities \(P(X_{ij} = 1 | \delta = 1)\) for each item is given by

delta <- 1

MCMC using JAGS

Let d[i] be the latent indicator vector of the diseased class, i.e. d[i] = 1 if individual i is diseased, and d[i] = 0 if healthy. If d[i] = 1 then each item X[i, j] is Bernoulli with success probability pi[j, 1], and conversely if d[i] = 0 then each item X[i, j] is Bernoulli with success probability pi[j, 2]. The sensitivities are the first column of pi, and the specificities are one minus the second column of pi. Set diffuse priors for the prevalence tau and all entries in the p by 2 matrix pi. The JAGS model is as follows:

mod.jags.lcm <- "model{
  for (i in 1:n) {
    d[i] ~ dbern(tau)
    for (j in 1:p) {
      pi.x[i, j] <- d[i] * pi[j, 1] + (1 - d[i]) * pi[j, 2]
      X[i, j] ~ dbern(pi.x[i, j])
    }
  }

  # Priors
  tau ~ dbeta(1, 1)
  for (j in 1:p) {
    pi[j, 1] ~ dbeta(1, 1)
    pi[j, 2] ~ dbeta(1, 1)
    # u[j] ~ dnorm(0, 0.001) I(0,)
    # pi[j, 2] = phi(probit(pi[j, 1]) - u[j])
  }

  # Sensitivities and specificities
  for (j  in 1:p) {
    sens[j] <- pi[j, 1]
    spec[j] <- 1 - pi[j, 2]
  }

}

#data# X, n, p
#monitor# tau, sens, spec, deviance
"

Supply the following initial values:

inits <- list(
  tau = 0.1,
  d = rep(0, n),
  pi = matrix(c(0.9, 0.1), nrow = p, ncol = 2, byrow = TRUE)
)

Now run the model.

(mod <- run.jags(mod.jags.lcm, n.chains = 8, sample = 4000, thin = 1, 
                 inits = inits, burnin = 1600, adapt = 400, method = "parallel"))

Latent Class Model with Random Effects

To relax the assumption of independence conditional on the true disease status, introduce individual specific random effects.

\[ \begin{gather} X_{ij}|\delta_i,u_i \sim \text{Bern}(\pi_{ij}) \\ \pi_{ij} = \begin{cases} \Phi(\beta_{0j} + \sigma_{0}u_i) &\text{if } \delta_i = 0 \\ \Phi(\beta_{1j} + \sigma_{1}u_i) &\text{if } \delta_i = 1 \\ \end{cases} \\ \delta_i \sim \text{Bern}(\tau) \\ u_i \sim \text{N}(0,1) \end{gather} \]

The sensitivities and specificities are given by

\[ \begin{align*} \text{P}(X_{ij} = 1 | \delta_i = 1) &= \Phi\left( \frac{\beta_{1j}}{(1 + \sigma_1^2)^{1/2}} \right) \\ \text{P}(X_{ij} = 0 | \delta_i = 0) &= 1 - \Phi\left( \frac{\beta_{0j}}{(1 + \sigma_0^2)^{1/2}} \right) \\ \end{align*} \]

Likelihood-based method (randomLCA package)

(mod.lcmre <- randomLCA(X, nclass = 2, probit = TRUE,  random = TRUE, 
                        quadpoints = 61, constload = TRUE, byclass = TRUE, 
                        seed = 123))

MCMC using JAGS

mod.jags.lcmre <- "
model{
  for (i in 1:n) {
    d[i] ~ dbern(tau)
    u[i] ~ dnorm(0, 1)
    for (j in 1:p) {
      u0[i, j] <- beta[j, 1] + sigma[1] * u[i]  # healthy 
      u1[i, j] <- beta[j, 2] + sigma[2] * u[i]  # diseased
      pi.x[i, j] <- d[i] * phi(u1[i, j]) + (1 - d[i]) * phi(u0[i, j])
      X[i, j] ~ dbern(pi.x[i, j])
    }
  }

  # Priors
  tau ~ dbeta(1,1)
  for (j in 1:p) {
    beta[j, 1] ~ dnorm(0, 0.1)
    beta[j, 2] ~ dnorm(0, 0.1)
  }
  sigma[1] ~ dgamma(1, 1)
  sigma[2] ~ dgamma(1, 1)

  # Sensitivities and specificities
  for (j  in 1:p) {
    sens[j] <- phi(beta[j, 1] / sqrt(1 + pow(sigma[1], 2)))
    spec[j] <- 1 - phi(beta[j, 2] / sqrt(1 + pow(sigma[2], 2)))
  }
}

#data# X, n, p
#monitor# tau, sens, spec, deviance
"

Supply the following initial values:

inits <- list(
  tau = 0.1,
  d = rep(0, n),
  beta = matrix(c(1, -1), nrow = p, ncol = 2, byrow = TRUE),
  sigma = c(1.5, 1.5)
)

Now run the model.
